abstract: A union in Nevada, the third state to vote in the Democratic primary, told presidential candidates that health care, specifically keeping union health care, is what’s on their members’ minds.
snippet: A union in Nevada, the third state to vote in the Democratic primary, told presidential candidates that health care, specifically keeping union health care, is what’s on their members’ minds.
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — The union member had a pointed question for Elizabeth Warren: “What is your plan to make sure we keep our community health clinic?”

abstract: Public opinion has shifted about impeachment, but not about the president. Here’s what that means.
snippet: Public opinion has shifted about impeachment, but not about the president. Here’s what that means.
lead_paragraph: Picture this: a president enjoying the lowest unemployment rate in decades and a booming stock market. He is about to notch a major legislative victory with the passage of a significant trade deal, has appointed two Supreme Court justices and has signed a major tax bill into law. Most voters say they’re better off financially than when he took office, according to polling this week.

abstract: Mr. Biden would roll back President Trump’s immigration policies but would not decriminalize unauthorized border crossings, in contrast with his progressive rivals.
snippet: Mr. Biden would roll back President Trump’s immigration policies but would not decriminalize unauthorized border crossings, in contrast with his progressive rivals.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Wednesday released an immigration plan that calls for undoing President Trump’s policies and acknowledges “pain” caused by deportations that occurred during his time as vice president, but does not endorse the decriminalization of unauthorized border crossings, a contrast with more progressive rivals such as Senators Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren.

headline_main: Could Politics Be Fairer? Two New Books Say Yes
headline_print_headline: How to Mend Our Broken Politics

abstract: The presidential candidates need to stop demurring and fully reject Trump’s approach.
snippet: The presidential candidates need to stop demurring and fully reject Trump’s approach.
lead_paragraph: When it comes to trade policy with China, the Democratic presidential candidates face a conundrum. They don’t want to sign onto President Trump’s endless, chaotic, pain-over-gain trade war, yet they don’t want to appear weak or appeasing of China’s trade practices.

abstract: Big election days like Super Tuesday will be more demographically representative (hurts Biden). There will be fewer caucuses (hurts Sanders).
snippet: Big election days like Super Tuesday will be more demographically representative (hurts Biden). There will be fewer caucuses (hurts Sanders).
lead_paragraph: When the Democratic primaries start in less than two months, they will lead off as usual with four familiar early states. What follows next is different. It’s not so different as to be unrecognizable, but enough to upend conventional wisdom about the path to the nomination.

abstract: They accused President Trump of having abused his power and “betrayed the nation.”
snippet: They accused President Trump of having abused his power and “betrayed the nation.”
lead_paragraph: The impeachment articles that House Democrats drafted mirror the ones the Judiciary Committee approved in 1974 when it charged President Richard Nixon with abuse of power and contempt of Congress. Here are some key excerpts, followed by a brief description of what they mean.

abstract: It is the only thing to do if our country’s democracy is to survive.
snippet: It is the only thing to do if our country’s democracy is to survive.
lead_paragraph: Impeaching a president is the most consequential thing our Congress can do — other than declaring war. So, after great consideration, I say: President Trump not only should be impeached, he must be impeached if America’s democracy is to remain intact.
